Rajchl promises that in the event of his election will begin to work hard.
He wants to introduce systemic changes, and the members of the executive committee responsible for individual football fields.
He also promised to resolve the case Bohemians to improve relations with UEFA and FIFA to bring more money into the football and otherwise to continue the work of the previous presiding Ivan Hašek has begun.
"As chairman, I would like to focus on the football as a whole."
Starting from the international contacts with UEFA and FIFA, on the national selection, professional football, football for the young people. "
"I do not want to say that I want to do everything alone," said Rajchl in talks for ČTK.
"I am a team player and would therefore like to distribute the powers of the executive committee that each member pays a certain area."
And I will be distributing tough tasks, so that the football in every segment is moving forward. "
Moreover, many not just delighted, because they, rather than to criticize the work of others, should begin to work really hard, "he added.
Because of the critical atmosphere in the football movement have not to stand at all.
"I know that I am working 20 hours a day."
"But I must know that it makes sense and that people are behind me, I do not use a stick between the legs and every step that I am put into question," he said as an explanation of why he hesitated.
"Many people told me that I should not give up, because otherwise others would do it."
"This is confidence that we must not squander," he said.
It is allegedly motivated him, should be able to continue the work he has begun under Hašek.
"In two years we have accomplished a great deal of work and I will not just throw away."
"There have been trials started only in a few years to play, and I would like to see someone cut off," he said, and expresses its concern at the fact that in the event that the other candidate - Miroslav Pelta elected, the situation could return to the days before Hašek could return.
"I believe in systematic approach, and that is something that does not Mirek Pelta."
"Behind him, above all, people who would make the football so that he would be only for exclusivity."
I think we can accuse some, but not that I would be biased. "
"I am trying to be objective."
"I want football for everybody, because it all goes well, and not just the man," said Rajchl.
It also contradicts the assertion that he was only a leader of the Czech Republic.
"Even if some people say the opposite, I have to do what is best for Moravia."
"For example, it is time to consider whether the league should not be divided into a Czech and Moravian part, whose winners in each of the first league."
"Then it could not happen that today only three Moravian clubs play in the league, particularly for the young players in Moravia is a problem," said Rajchl.
Because the head of the Pilsner club Tomáš Paclík joined the battle for the post of chairman, Rajchl does not have the courage to assess his chances that he will be elected.
"I feel a strong support in the Czech Chamber, which has been elected to its deputy chairman and now recognises that clear successes are behind me," Rajchl led to the saving of tens of millions of kronor on unfavorable contracts, the agreement of television contracts and the negotiations with the lottery law as its success.
On the other hand, it is partly the fault of the association was not in a single direction.
While Pelta, he says, "he was disqualified from the outset, the Czech football with greater confidence," he considers the second rivals - Paclík for a strong candidate, the football really have something to offer.
"No one can question that he Pilsen in just one year has done an excellent job."
"He should be elected, he would probably things continue, Ivan Hašek has begun, and the personnel in the commissions he would obviously not fundamentally change."
He would certainly not want to altered just on his favour, "Rajchl ruling on his rivals.
Europe's most beautiful pools
Leap in the dark
By Julia Stanek
Planschbecken Ufo-Optik, future pools in Budapest: anyone who travels through Europe can be seen blue miracle - and after a city tour or a wandering Sprudelbädern hide behind the tired legs.
A book shows, where wellness in the water is the most beautiful.
When Iris Meder in the past one and a half years on research trip, was not lacking in their luggage: her bathing costume.
Rücklings on the water, they looked in elaborate domes, they swam Putten marble, they waited in the basin, and was meticulously restored from Jugendstilschwimmhallen.
Gefiel her a bath, she took in her notiz book - all the knowledge worth details about the design and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools answer architecture historian Meder in this way - and it is now in her book "bathing pleasures:" People's swimming halls in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
By 13 countries, their "journey to the most extraordinary spas in Central Europe ": in Germany, Austria and Switzerland, it visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland, and a town in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46 - year-old German is a true Badekultur-Enthusiastin.
In sport, it does not have much in the, says Meder - only in the water is different.
Annoying that swimming fans come with blue Kacheln and chlorine smell, while jogger inhale the betörenden smell of Fichtenwäldern inhale or happy Vogelgezwitscher listening in the park.
"One day I asked myself why swimming pools must always be so ugly," says the Meder living in Vienna.
"So I began to collect beautiful baths."
Water doubled architecture
The wellness factor in bathrooms geplätscher in the basin and ethereal sauna oils - is so great, because all sense, so Meder.
And if the builders have been trouble swimming halls can be a real Augenschmaus: "Instead of a floor in dipping water surface."
"It is transparent, on the other hand, reflects the beauty of the whole building."
All doubled blend: high vaults, colorful Kacheln, bretter.
The kleinformatige picture band "bathing pleasures" gives 190 pages of knowledge about the architecture and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all, for a leap into the blue.
Remarkable specimens discovered the pool Sammlerin Meder with her research in Hungary.
In addition, sumptuous Heilbads such as the 100 years old Széchenyi-Bad in Budapest, they found a nitrathaltiges waters in an urigen Karsthöhle (Höhlenbad Miskolc-Tapolca), as well as a Thermalbad, whose basin filled with alkalihaltigem water and are in a flaschenförmigen building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Spectacular prospects, however, offer many heated pools in Switzerland and Austria, while the Zurich Dachbad the whole city, it is an external pool Bads in St Anton on the snow-covered Arlberg look - and, in the, there is a window from which you can monitor the activities of the Ski-Piste.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design expects bathers in length field: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like an Ufo landed in the Alps.
> From three upwards open Schales dampft in the winter, while in the background, the mountains of the Ötztals out in the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
It is not in every swimming pool, the pool collector Meder the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal spas smell after sulphur in the Árpád-bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba stinks to be so much for fuel oil, which is difficult to believe in a Gesundheitsbad landed.
The smell comes from the alkali hydrogenkarbonathaltigen water, which is almost black and whose silt a stain on the skin, once you slip into the pool - a wellness experience.
In one place was Iris Meder in their search for beautiful bathing sites, however, also disappointed: When they free and sun in the Czech Bad Luhatschowitz wanted to visit, they found a cordoned off area.
The 1902 by the architect Duan Jurkovic bath has now been closed.
When Meder a glance through the verwitterten windows of the red-Weis-yellow art nouveau building, she saw how weeds between the tiles grown.
It the decline has countered, however, in a beautiful swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais hot springs at Bad Wildbad.
Three construction has this bad already behind; it can detect not only neoromanische elements from the time of its establishment in 1844, but also a maurische hall in Alhambra style, which was added in 1900.
Since the 1995 thorough modernization is the Palais hot springs pool kennerin Lieblingsbad iris Meder - and not just because they originally comes from the Black Forest.
"It is quite an achievement, so different Baustile at such a great unity," says Meder.
With such a palace is the Tauchgang in thermal pool only incidental.
Agricultural speculation
German bank leaves commodity business
Christian Teevs
The Deutsche Bank business with agricultural commodities?
According to online information, Josef Ackermann has appointed a working group to examine the impact of speculation for the poor of the world.
In January, the CEO's wants to draw conclusions.
Hamburg.
The matter is clear: 84 percent of Germans for the German citizens find it unacceptable, according to a study that banks with agricultural commodities such as wheat or corn.
Two thirds of respondents want the Deutsche Bank and other lending institutions out of this business, because it exacerbates the problems of the poorest people in the world.
This is the result of a Forsa survey commissioned by the consumer organisation Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report that Foodwatch in mid-October.
It shows the author Harald Schumann, betting on the global commodity markets prices soar - and the banks are partly to blame for the global hunger problem.
The campaign of consumer protection is directed specifically against Deutsche Bank chief Josef Ackermann, even if big banks like Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley.
Commodity bets were originally intended for traders hedge against price fluctuations.
But now, most experts agree that the gamblers have decoupled from supply and demand - and at the expense of the poorest profits.
Unlike the U.S. competitors Ackermann responded to the criticism: he promised to investigate the allegations and said that no business is worth it "the good name of the Deutsche Bank to gamble."
According to information from SPIEGEL ONLINE an International working group is currently examining the allegations from the Foodwatch Report.
By the end of the year is expected to be completed, then the results will be presented to the board of Deutsche Bank, with a recommendation on how to deal with it.
At the end of January, the head of the bank wants to tell us what consequences.
In the end, could be a reduction in the commodity business, or even the complete departure.
Ackermann fusses over his image
Foodwatch chief Thilo Bode welcomed the news, but at the same time, however, his criticism of the financial industry: "the betting on rising prices of food particularly dramatic shows how reckless banks today, the common good."
Ackermann stand as a top bank lobbyist now, especially in the duty.
"The Deutsche Bank must remove all assets from its portfolio, where money will be used for betting on food prices," said Bode.
"No matter whether it is Mr Ackermann hunger suffering people or the reputation of the German Bank."
The insight of Ackermann is surprising at first glance, it is clear, however, that the CEO's just a few months before his departure from office would like to make a perfect picture.
On Monday, the Deutsche Bank announced that the CEO differently than planned will not change in the supervisory board.
In a move away from the controversial agricultural speculation he could improve his image.
And it needs for possible losses to be little fun - after all, his successor would have to do so.
Every second would cancel commodity crops
Foodwatch is trying to keep the pressure on the manager.
So far, more than 30,000 Internet users took part in the campaign of the organisation.
On Tuesday, Bode published the poll, for which the institute Forsa on 7 and 8 November has interviewed 1001 people.
Just 11 percent think it is legitimate that the Deutsche Bank facilities, where bets on food prices.
Many bank customers would also draw personal conclusions when they learn that their bank is involved in such transactions: Every second, according to the survey would terminate all installations where money is flowing into commodity speculation.
43% would advise friends of such a bank, 49 percent said they consider to terminate their accounts and to switch to another institution.
21er house in Vienna
The umgezogene pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with ups, downs and happy ending: the Austrian World Expo pavilion from Brussels in 1958 prices, was in Vienna for the museum, was empty and descended.
Now, he is being reopened as an exhibition house.
If dreams of modern postwar architecture, clear forms, glass halls, courageous swings and new building materials, which are typical of the belief in the technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of Karl Schwanzer architects for the Brussels World Expo 1958 is a good and famous example.
Schwanzers pavilion at the Eurovision Song Contest Architecture for his easy and steel glass design.
The building is seen as a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that at the next World Expo in Austria pavilion built.
With his legendary BMW Vierzylinderhaus plus schüsselartigem Nebenbau in Munich, he became internationally famous.
His temporary Ausstellungsbau planned pavilion of the world Expo in the Swiss garden at the Vienna South station converted and in 1962 opened a museum of the 20th century - the "20s home" has been called it.
This was the building but neither physically and technically as a museum - no walls on the slopes of the art, not a good climate.
Nevertheless, it has been used for so long, until the contemporary art in Vienna, a new house.
Since 2001, the building was empty and more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz converted the pavilion, he is now "21er House" and will in future be used as a museum of contemporary art.
On Tuesday night, the museum opened Belvedere, which includes the house, where the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every respect.
The new start Agnes Husslein-Arco, the 2007 new director of the Austrian gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, doctorate art historian with considerable career, among other things, in the youth as Eiskunstläufererin later with Sotheby's, the Guggenheim museum and founding director of the museum of modern Salzburg, strongly defended the with politicians and conservationists monument, they acquired public funds and private sponsorship money and use.
Besides contemporary art works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba should be issued by the eponymous foundation, a café and a bookshop, it should be, and an office house had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
The implementation was Krischanitz the ideal occupation.
It is not only because he Joseph Olbrichs Secession in Vienna sensitive converted and enlarged and had won the competition, but because he Schwanzer has studied at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion for him, "enormously important place ," where he" almost every weekend "the exhibitions.
He knew the draft, and he knew the problems of the building, which was already in his transfer to Vienna and his Umnutzung of generosity and easily lost.
In the current restructuring, there were far greater problems: the building was "an Energieschleuder," says Krischanitz.
The profils windows were replaced outside glass fibre verstärktes insulating glass and the glass roof replaced by special security glass.
Kältebrücken steel girders have been strengthened or replaced, and asbestgefüllte blankets have been refurbished.
Two shells made room for the new use, an abgesenkter light gap between house and road for the Belichtung, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the easy Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors are left, the house is removed in the old rotbraun Rostschutz-Farbton.
And the cinema is even exactly as it was before.
And all this under strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found, which is a good thing, and it is cheap and Denkmalschutzamt liked," says Krischanitz and highlights an abrasive soil in -.
Despite all the constraints, problems and to the building is flexible and easy.
It would have been difficult with the pavilion, "the came from Brussels," said Krischanitz recently, a typical "drop in history."
So an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "create a real awareness."
In this case, the 21er house but not in the wrong place, because it is an urban fluke: if the Swiss garden is completely new planned "Central Station Quartier," with office and residential buildings.
And another stroke will occur: the 21er house could increase by another Krischanitz construction, because the Sammlerin Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin temporary art hall, and we hear that they have been negotiating with the city a neighbourly location in the Swiss garden.
