Mass slaughter on a personal level
Sensitive and generous begins Peter Englunds new book "beauty and horror. A history of the First World War, tells in nineteen fates" with a long list of players to heart.
Here is a tip on how to proceed: Cut off the side of caution and make it to your readers.
They are the people in Englunds romanhafter narrative know each other very well, and these people as your GPS function as a beacon in these few moments, in which you as Englunds men and women lost in the fog of war and are deprived of your illusions.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which determines the Nobel Prize for literature.
He has written an unusual book that he was not incorrect as "a work of anti-history."
It contains only a few big names, important contracts or famous battles. There is little ambassadors, racing reporters or discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is less a book about what happened, he says, but rather "a book about how it was." it is about "feelings, impressions, experiences and sentiments."
"Beauty and horror" almost war experiences of 20 more or less concealed men and women on both sides of the war of school girls and Botanikern to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and office workers.
Some of these people are heroes.
Some prisoners of war, lose limb, crazy or die.
Each of these lives flackert such as the Votivkerzen in a church, some, while others lapse.
Englunds book differs from the usual history books.
It also corrected the idea that the First World war was just the devastating war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and horror" with experts on other war zones: the Alps, the Balkans, the Ostfront, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are bees baskets, celebrates Christmas under the pyramids in Egypt, tsetse flies are an insoluble problem.
This is a very moving book almost from the outset.
The war flooded the lives of these people as a natural disaster like a hurricane Katrina, which reeks of Kordit.
Imagine that you are a woman who is at home with their children, and cannon fire in the distance. You or you take the flight?
Who is at all?
Hardly anyone understands what is happening or why this war is being waged at all.
"There is a lack of facts," Englund says, "with assumptions, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and horror" individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard root, a young German ship sailors.
Their stories were mainly memories, letters and other already published material.
Their reports can be frightening or simple, but they are very vivid in Englunds of the accumulation of small moments losing in.
Many of them act of shortages and Behelfen.
In the history of a German school girl, he told: "spare everywhere."
"Spare coffee, wrong aluminium, false eraser, paper, wood buttons."
He tells us of the dinner in Germany.
He describes "meat made from pressed rice and Hammelfett (and most recently was served with a false bones from wood), tobacco, which was made from dried roots and dried potato bowls, shoes, which were besohlt with wood."
There was, as he noted, "837 registered food substitute foods that were allowed in the manufacture of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitute."
