The stark contradictory impressions illustrate the difficult relationship between the military and the most distant, sometimes admiring American public.
The troops are showered with praise for their victims.
But the praise has its price, service members say.
The public is increasingly behaving as if their people in uniform suffering.
"We were not victims," said Brigadier general Sean B. MacFarland, who commanded the troops in Iraq and will soon go to Afghanistan.
"But it is the only way of support, to put ourselves in the role of unfortunate souls."
The issue is extremely sensitive for military leaders, who do not want ungrateful or in dispute with the public they serve.
They also have recognized that the anger, the returning troops in the last few years of the Vietnam War, was far worse.
As a result there are discussions about compassion in silence and private between war veterans.
After his two sons have returned from battles with the marines, warned Colonel ex-army Mark Cancian that people outside the military world their service could be seen from two different perspectives.
Some would view them with a sense of awe, as they defeated rebels and travelled to exotic places.
Others would wonder whether a "angry, violent veteran beneath the surface," said Cancian, who had fought in Iraq and a senior government posts in Washington after his return.
