"If you are talking about your service, you must keep the negative impressions about it," Cancian said his sons.
The lack of ease of the military is rooted in part in the lack of interest in the war.
Services on the battlefield of a country that has little experience with the military and little benefit in the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, rarely singled out as praise.
"We as a nation, not military heroism, as it was in the Second World War was absolutely normal," said Lieutenant General David Barno, the U.S. troops in Afghanistan.
Instead, the praise of politicians and the public largely due to the suffering of a service member.
Troops find recognition for the number of attacks they have endured, the number of friends who have lost them, or for the severity of their injuries.
