Japan will be reborn after the earthquake
The GDP is growing by 1,5%, thanks to the domestic consumption and stop the cycle of free fall from the beginning of March
Since last March was paralyzed the Japanese economy, which is still in the recovery after the devastating earthquake, which einmündete into a nuclear crisis and the worst catastrophe that Japan had lived through the second World War.
The initial estimates of the government in Tokyo evaluated the property damage at $300 000, a which, despite the difficult world economic situation.
After three quarters of case, the details of the gross domestic product between July and September, finally to close this chapter: GDP grew by 1,5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% of the year hochgerechnete quota.
In the second quarter, the measured value - in Japan the year begins in March 2012 - also means the fastest growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery can be explained in part through the sale of machinery for the rebuilding of the earthquake and subsequent tsunami devastated areas.
In fact, the companies increased their investments by 1,1% compared with the decline of 0,9% for capital expenditures, which were recorded from January to March, the first decline after six months of relentless increases.
Nevertheless, the real turnaround of the Japanese economy is not exclusively from Keynesian stimulus, using the crisis to build infrastructure or build new ones.
Awakened Japan in particular, thanks to the development of domestic consumption, which accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable rose by 1%, initiated by the growing spending on cars, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of yen
Tokyo has entrusted to the domestic market, after the yen - the Japanese currency - in one of the "safe haven currencies" of investors fleeing the debt crisis in the euro zone and the gloomy forecasts for the U.S. a., a privilege as a gravestone rests on the accounts of the export companies.
With a stronger currency are the products more expensive abroad, a serious problem for a country whose economy is based on the health of the major technology producers.
Toyota and Sony, for example, led their weak business results from July to September on the listing of the yen.
While the markets continue to besieged the peripheral EU countries, the government Yoshihiko Noda vigilant.
"We must pay attention to the continuing risks, for example, the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday, the Secretary of State for economic policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
The prospects are not really very aufheiternd.
The Organisation for economic Cooperation and development (OECD) said that most of the member states in September contained clearer signs of a slowdown in economic development.
The indicator, which ahead-takes the turning points of the world economy, brought to light that the brakes would be the biggest economic powers.
Because he fell by four tenths up to 100.4 points compared to 100.8 in August.
The euro zone is even below the average of 100, after it fell by eight tenths on 99.13 points.
