Why is the unemployment rate for disabled people in such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are searching for a job.
Today begins the 15th week of work for the disabled. "
Despite the purposeful public policy, which was introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people has always been twice as high as the average value: 19% Arbeitlosigkeit 9% of the total population.
Discouraging?
"No, Éric Blanchet, director-general of the Association of Adapt" week of work for the disabled. "
"The fifteen years of progress."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, a great deal still remains to be done."
It must be said, however, that many obstacles remain for disabled people remain before they get a job.
More often, it is the elderly: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them have no baccalaureate and there are only 10,000 people among the 2.3 million students in higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% of the disabled, compared with 38% in the overall average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make a fresh start working, and the "heart of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association in 1992, the company is helping to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
The underlying implication, mentalities, certainly, but slowly.
A in April by the Association of IMS-Entreprendre for the magazine La Cité study, which surveyed managers have "a weak level of knowledge about disabled people," the "over-represented" of people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually less well-off. "
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to the employment target of 6% disabled workers, which was enshrined in an Act of 1987.
The latter, from the 2008 figures point to a ratio of 2,6%.
"We are now at about 3%," said Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organisation, which is tasked with recovering contributions from companies that flout the law.
The proof: the number of "charges" plants has been reduced, as well as the amount of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, zahlenmäβig from 59.000 to 46.000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The law of 2005, which provides increases, created a strong pressure on the company, said Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement is also a real awareness, especially among the large firms groups."
According to the Ministry for work only 59% of the plants between 20 and 49 people disabled workers, companies with 100 to 199 employees compared to 82%.
